    "src": "/pasted-image-20201026231441png",
    "alt": "Pasted image 20201026231441.png"
  })), "\nThis may not be truly revolutionary thinking here, but the thought occurred to me this evening. The great thing about servers is that, in a tightly controlled environment, you can easily scale capacity to meet demand by adding more hardware. When you specialize servers to specific tasks, such as virtualization (compute), file sharing (storage), database serving, web service, email, print, etc, the 'scaling to demand' becomes even easier. This is the approach taken by most large corporate offices today (and of the last two to three decades). The concept of a microservice, while seemingly completely different, is actually no more than an incremental extension of this specialization. In fact, I bet it was invented by some guy going 'hey, if we can just throw another rack at our email service when the load doubles, why can't I do the same with my message queue in this forum site I'm hosting?' "), mdx("h2", null, "While I'm on the topic..."), mdx("p", null, mdx("img", _extends({
